    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Goblin management,\" you ask? Ah, a delightful term for the delicate dance of microbial ecology! When I say that, I mean ensuring the *right* kind of little critters are happy and fed, much like ensuring the goblins have their favorite shiny trinkets and enough stale bread to keep them from raiding the pantry. If the ratios are off, the chemical mechanism that causes the bubbles to cease is essentially a metabolic slowdown, or a shift in dominance.\n\nThe bubbles, which are primarily carbon dioxide ($\\text{CO}_2$), are the byproduct of fermentation. The yeast, *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* (and others), consumes the simple sugars in your flour and converts them into ethanol and $\\text{CO}_2$. If the ratio of flour to water is wrong, or if the starter is too old and acidic, the yeast can become stressed. Stress, in microbial terms, means they slow down their metabolic rate—they stop producing gas as rapidly because they are either starved or overwhelmed by the environment.\n\nThink of it like this: if you feed a group of tiny, industrious, but easily irritated goblins too much of a difficult-to-digest root vegetable instead of their favorite sweet berries, they won't produce",
